04814nam a22005775i 9780822386001DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20042004ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1229161056  a97808223860017 a10.1515/97808223860012doi  a(DE-B1597)553775  a(OCoLC)1125876814  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aU428.S83bG54 2004 7aPOL0120002bisacsh04a320.97/071/52221 aGill, Lesley, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe School of the Americas :bMilitary Training and Political Violence in the Americas /cLesley Gill; ed. by Gilbert M. Joseph, Emily S. Rosenberg. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (300 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican encounters/global interactions : 3900tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue: The Teflon Assassin -- tIntroduction: The Military, Political Violence, and Impunity -- tChapter 1: Georgia Not on Their Minds -- tChapter 2: De-Mining Humanitarianism -- tChapter 3: Foot Soldiers of the U.S. Empire -- tChapter 4: Pathways to Power -- tChapter 5: Strategic Alliances -- tChapter 6: Human Wrongs and Rights -- tChapter 7: Disordering the Andes -- tChapter 8: Targeting the ‘‘School of Assassins’’ -- tConclusion: The School of America -- tNotes -- tReferences Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLocated at Fort Benning in Columbus, Georgia, the School of the Americas (soa) is a U.S. Army center that has trained more than sixty thousand soldiers and police, mostly from Latin America, in counterinsurgency and combat-related skills since it was founded in 1946. So widely documented is the participation of the School’s graduates in torture, murder, and political repression throughout Latin America that in 2001 the School officially changed its name to the Western Hemisphere Institute for Security Cooperation. Lesley Gill goes behind the façade and presents a comprehensive portrait of the School of the Americas. Talking to a retired Colombian general accused by international human rights organizations of terrible crimes, sitting in on classes, accompanying soa students and their families to an upscale local mall, listening to coca farmers in Colombia and Bolivia, conversing with anti-soa activists in the cramped office of the School of the Americas Watch—Gill exposes the School’s institutionalization of state-sponsored violence, the havoc it has wrought in Latin America, and the strategies used by activists seeking to curtail it.Based on her unprecedented level of access to the School of the Americas, Gill describes the School’s mission and training methods and reveals how its students, alumni, and officers perceive themselves in relation to the dirty wars that have raged across Latin America. Assessing the School’s role in U.S. empire-building, she shows how Latin America’s brightest and most ambitious military officers are indoctrinated into a stark good-versus-evil worldview, seduced by consumer society and the “American dream,” and enlisted as proxies in Washington’s war against drugs and “subversion.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aImperialism. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh1 aJoseph, Gilbert M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRosenberg, Emily S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822386001zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822386001423Coveruhttps://www